Note:
Runa Standard Library: Deque (Double-Ended Queue)

Provides a comprehensive double-ended queue with natural language operations for adding, removing, and inspecting elements from both ends. Advanced features include rotation, bulk operations, slicing, searching, sorting, and performance optimizations.

Features include:
- Core deque operations (add/remove from both ends)
- Rotation and shifting operations
- Bulk operations and batch processing
- Slicing and indexing with bounds checking
- Searching and filtering operations
- Sorting and ordering operations
- Memory-efficient operations
- Thread-safe operations (when supported)
:End Note

Type Deque is Dictionary with:
    items as List[Any]
    maxlen as Optional[Integer]

Note: Core Deque Operations
Process called "create_deque" that returns Deque:
    Return dictionary with:
        items as list containing
        maxlen as None

Process called "create_deque_with_maxlen" that takes maxlen as Integer returns Deque:
    Return dictionary with:
        items as list containing
        maxlen as maxlen

Process called "add_to_front" that takes deque as Deque and value as Any returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let maxlen be deque["maxlen"]
    Let new_items be list containing value
    For each item in items:
        Add item to new_items
    If maxlen is not None:
        If length of new_items is greater than maxlen:
            Let new_items be slice_list with lst as new_items and start as 0 and end as maxlen
    Set deque["items"] to new_items
    Return deque

Process called "add_to_back" that takes deque as Deque and value as Any returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let maxlen be deque["maxlen"]
    Let new_items be list containing
    For each item in items:
        Add item to new_items
    Add value to new_items
    If maxlen is not None:
        If length of new_items is greater than maxlen:
            Let new_items be slice_list with lst as new_items and start as 1 and end as maxlen plus 1
    Set deque["items"] to new_items
    Return deque

Process called "remove_from_front" that takes deque as Deque returns (Deque, Any):
    Let items be deque["items"]
    If length of items is equal to 0:
        Throw IndexError with message "Deque is empty"
    Let value be items[0]
    Let new_items be list containing
    For i from 1 to length of items:
        Add items[i] to new_items
    Set deque["items"] to new_items
    Return (deque, value)

Process called "remove_from_back" that takes deque as Deque returns (Deque, Any):
    Let items be deque["items"]
    If length of items is equal to 0:
        Throw IndexError with message "Deque is empty"
    Let last_index be length of items minus 1
    Let value be items[last_index]
    Let new_items be list containing
    For i from 0 to last_index:
        Add items[i] to new_items
    Set deque["items"] to new_items
    Return (deque, value)

Process called "peek_front" that takes deque as Deque returns Any:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    If length of items is equal to 0:
        Throw IndexError with message "Deque is empty"
    Return items[0]

Process called "peek_back" that takes deque as Deque returns Any:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    If length of items is equal to 0:
        Throw IndexError with message "Deque is empty"
    Let last_index be length of items minus 1
    Return items[last_index]

Process called "deque_length" that takes deque as Deque returns Integer:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Return length of items

Process called "deque_is_empty" that takes deque as Deque returns Boolean:
    Return deque_length with deque as deque is equal to 0

Process called "deque_is_full" that takes deque as Deque returns Boolean:
    Let maxlen be deque["maxlen"]
    If maxlen is None:
        Return false
    Let maxlen_val be maxlen
    Return deque_length with deque as deque is equal to maxlen_val

Note: Rotation and Shifting Operations
Process called "rotate" that takes deque as Deque and n as Integer returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    If length is equal to 0:
        Return deque
    Let normalized_n be n modulo length
    If normalized_n is equal to 0:
        Return deque
    If normalized_n is greater than 0:
        Let split_point be length minus normalized_n
        Let first_part be slice_list with lst as items and start as 0 and end as split_point
        Let second_part be slice_list with lst as items and start as split_point and end as length
        Let rotated_items be concatenate_lists with lst1 as second_part and lst2 as first_part
    Otherwise:
        Let split_point be abs with x as normalized_n
        Let first_part be slice_list with lst as items and start as 0 and end as split_point
        Let second_part be slice_list with lst as items and start as split_point and end as length
        Let rotated_items be concatenate_lists with lst1 as second_part and lst2 as first_part
    Set deque["items"] to rotated_items
    Return deque

Process called "rotate_left" that takes deque as Deque and n as Integer returns Deque:
    Return rotate with deque as deque and n as negative n

Process called "rotate_right" that takes deque as Deque and n as Integer returns Deque:
    Return rotate with deque as deque and n as n

Process called "shift_left" that takes deque as Deque and n as Integer returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    If n is greater than or equal to length:
        Set deque["items"] to list containing
        Return deque
    Let shifted_items be slice_list with lst as items and start as n and end as length
    Set deque["items"] to shifted_items
    Return deque

Process called "shift_right" that takes deque as Deque and n as Integer returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    If n is greater than or equal to length:
        Set deque["items"] to list containing
        Return deque
    Let shifted_items be slice_list with lst as items and start as 0 and end as length minus n
    Set deque["items"] to shifted_items
    Return deque

Note: Bulk Operations
Process called "extend_front" that takes deque as Deque and values as List[Any] returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let maxlen be deque["maxlen"]
    Let new_items be concatenate_lists with lst1 as values and lst2 as items
    If maxlen is not None:
        Let maxlen_val be maxlen
        If length of new_items is greater than maxlen_val:
            Let new_items be slice_list with lst as new_items and start as 0 and end as maxlen_val
    Set deque["items"] to new_items
    Return deque

Process called "extend_back" that takes deque as Deque and values as List[Any] returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let maxlen be deque["maxlen"]
    Let new_items be concatenate_lists with lst1 as items and lst2 as values
    If maxlen is not None:
        Let maxlen_val be maxlen
        If length of new_items is greater than maxlen_val:
            Let new_items be slice_list with lst as new_items and start as length of new_items minus maxlen_val and end as length of new_items
    Set deque["items"] to new_items
    Return deque

Process called "clear" that takes deque as Deque returns Deque:
    Return set_field with obj as deque and field as "items" and value as create_list with elements as list containing

Process called "copy" that takes deque as Deque returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let maxlen be deque["maxlen"]
    Let new_items be list containing
    For each item in items:
        Add item to new_items
    Return dictionary with:
        items as new_items
        maxlen as maxlen

Note: Slicing and Indexing
Process called "get_at_index" that takes deque as Deque and index as Integer returns Any:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    If index is less than 0:
        Set index to length plus index
    If index is less than 0 or index is greater than or equal to length:
        Throw IndexError with message "Index out of bounds"
    Return items[index]

Process called "set_at_index" that takes deque as Deque and index as Integer and value as Any returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    If index is less than 0:
        Set index to length plus index
    If index is less than 0 or index is greater than or equal to length:
        Throw IndexError with message "Index out of bounds"
    Let new_items be list containing
    For i from 0 to length:
        If i is equal to index:
            Add value to new_items
        Otherwise:
            Add items[i] to new_items
    Set deque["items"] to new_items
    Return deque

Process called "slice_deque" that takes deque as Deque and start as Integer and end as Integer returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    If start is less than 0:
        Set start to length plus start
    If end is less than 0:
        Set end to length plus end
    If start is less than 0:
        Set start to 0
    If end is greater than length:
        Set end to length
    Let sliced_items be slice_list with lst as items and start as start and end as end
    Return dictionary with:
        items as sliced_items
        maxlen as None

Process called "reverse" that takes deque as Deque returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    Let reversed_items be create_list with elements as list containing
    For i from length minus 1 to negative 1 by negative 1:
        Add items[i] to reversed_items
    Set deque["items"] to reversed_items
    Return deque

Note: Searching and Filtering
Process called "index_of" that takes deque as Deque and value as Any returns Integer:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    For i from 0 to length of items:
        If items[i] is equal to value:
            Return i
    Throw ValueError with message "Value not found in deque"

Process called "index_of_from" that takes deque as Deque and value as Any and start as Integer returns Integer:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    If start is less than 0:
        Set start to length plus start
    If start is less than 0:
        Set start to 0
    For i from start to length:
        If items[i] is equal to value:
            Return i
    Throw ValueError with message "Value not found in deque"

Process called "count" that takes deque as Deque and value as Any returns Integer:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let count be 0
    For each item in items:
        If item is equal to value:
            Set count to count plus 1
    Return count

Process called "contains" that takes deque as Deque and value as Any returns Boolean:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    For each item in items:
        If item is equal to value:
            Return true
    Return false

Process called "filter" that takes deque as Deque and predicate as Process returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let filtered_items be create_list with elements as list containing
    For each item in items:
        If predicate with item as item:
            Add item to filtered_items
    Return dictionary with:
        items as filtered_items
        maxlen as None

Process called "map" that takes deque as Deque and transform as Process returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let mapped_items be create_list with elements as list containing
    For each item in items:
        Let transformed_item be transform with item as item
        Add transformed_item to mapped_items
    Return dictionary with:
        items as mapped_items
        maxlen as None

Note: Sorting and Ordering
Process called "sort" that takes deque as Deque returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let sorted_items be list containing
    For each item in items:
        Add item to sorted_items
    Sort sorted_items
    Set deque["items"] to sorted_items
    Return deque

Process called "sort_with_key" that takes deque as Deque and key_func as Process returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let sorted_items be list containing
    For each item in items:
        Add item to sorted_items
    Sort sorted_items using key_func
    Set deque["items"] to sorted_items
    Return deque

Process called "sort_reverse" that takes deque as Deque returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let sorted_items be list containing
    For each item in items:
        Add item to sorted_items
    Sort sorted_items in reverse order
    Set deque["items"] to sorted_items
    Return deque

Process called "is_sorted" that takes deque as Deque returns Boolean:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    For i from 1 to length:
        If items[i] is less than items[i minus 1]:
            Return false
    Return true

Process called "is_sorted_reverse" that takes deque as Deque returns Boolean:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    For i from 1 to length:
        If items[i] is greater than items[i minus 1]:
            Return false
    Return true

Note: Statistical Operations
Process called "min_element" that takes deque as Deque returns Any:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    If length of items is equal to 0:
        Throw ValueError with message "Deque is empty"
    Let min_val be items[0]
    For each item in items:
        If item is less than min_val:
            Set min_val to item
    Return min_val

Process called "max_element" that takes deque as Deque returns Any:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    If length of items is equal to 0:
        Throw ValueError with message "Deque is empty"
    Let max_val be items[0]
    For each item in items:
        If item is greater than max_val:
            Set max_val to item
    Return max_val

Process called "sum_elements" that takes deque as Deque returns Number:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let total be 0
    For each item in items:
        Set total to total plus item
    Return total

Process called "average" that takes deque as Deque returns Number:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    If length is equal to 0:
        Throw ValueError with message "Deque is empty"
    Let total be sum_elements with deque as deque
    Return total divided by length

Note: Memory and Performance Optimizations
Process called "compact" that takes deque as Deque returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let maxlen be deque["maxlen"]
    Let compacted_items be create_list with elements as list containing
    For each item in items:
        If item is not None:
            Add item to compacted_items
    Return dictionary with:
        items as compacted_items
        maxlen as maxlen

Process called "deduplicate" that takes deque as Deque returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let seen be set containing
    Let unique_items be create_list with elements as list containing
    For each item in items:
        If item not in seen:
            Add item to seen
            Add item to unique_items
    Return dictionary with:
        items as unique_items
        maxlen as None

Process called "shuffle" that takes deque as Deque returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let length be length of items
    Let shuffled_items be create_list with elements as list containing
    For each item in items:
        Add item to shuffled_items
    For i from length minus 1 to 1 by negative 1:
        Let j be random_int with min_val as 0 and max_val as i plus 1
        Let temp be shuffled_items[i]
        Set shuffled_items[i] to shuffled_items[j]
        Set shuffled_items[j] to temp
    Set deque["items"] to shuffled_items
    Return deque

Note: Utility Operations
Process called "to_list" that takes deque as Deque returns List[Any]:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let result be create_list with elements as list containing
    For each item in items:
        Add item to result
    Return result

Process called "from_list" that takes items as List[Any] returns Deque:
    Return dictionary with:
        items as items
        maxlen as None

Process called "from_list_with_maxlen" that takes items as List[Any] and maxlen as Integer returns Deque:
    Let length be length of items
    If length is greater than maxlen:
        Let items be slice_list with lst as items and start as length minus maxlen and end as length
    Return dictionary with:
        items as items
        maxlen as maxlen

Process called "get_maxlen" that takes deque as Deque returns Optional[Integer]:
    Return deque["maxlen"]

Process called "set_maxlen" that takes deque as Deque and maxlen as Integer returns Deque:
    Let items be deque["items"]
    Let current_length be length of items
    If current_length is greater than maxlen:
        Let items be slice_list with lst as items and start as current_length minus maxlen and end as current_length
    Return dictionary with:
        items as items
        maxlen as maxlen

Process called "slice_list" that takes lst as List[Any] and start as Integer and end as Integer returns List[Any]:
    Let new_lst be list containing
    For i from start to end:
        If i is less than length of lst:
            Add lst[i] to new_lst
    Return new_lst 